Dataset:

The variables are as follows:
Independent Variables:
Cement - kg in a m3 mixture
Blast - Blast Furnace Slag (kg in a m3 mixture)
Fly Ash Fly Ash (kg in a m3 mixture)
Water - Water (kg in a m3 mixture)
Superplasticizer Superplasticizer (kg in a m3 mixture)
CA - Coarse Aggregate (kg in a m3 mixture)
FA - Fine Aggregate (kg in a m3 mixture)
Age - Day (1~365)
Dependent Variable:
CMS - Concrete compressive strength

Theory:

Regression:

1.Regression is a Method of Finding a Relationship between a Independent Variable and Dependent Variable.
2.In Regression Model, the Dependent Variable is a Continuous Variable.
3.The dependent Variable is known as a Target.
4.The Independent Variables are called Features.
5.The dependent Variable relationship with respect to the Independent Variable is predicted.

Single Linear Regression:

1.In Single Linear Regression Model, there is only one Independent Variable and one dependent Variable.

Multivariate Regression Model:

1.There are Multiple Independent Variables and a Single Dependent Variable.

Linear Regression Modelling:

1.Linear Regression is based on a very simple formula.
2.Linear Regression is the basic technique to predict the value of an attribute.
3.The below snippet Explains the Linear Regression Model:

In Linear Regression Machine Learning Model, the objective is to Obtain the above Equation.

Where,
1.y is the Response/Target or Simply known as Dependent Variable.
2.x is the feature/predictor variable or simply known as independent Variable.
3.0 is the Intercept, the intercept defines the minimum value of Y when x=0. Meaning it is the constant value and its not dependable on x.
4.1 is the co-efficient of the independent variable.

1 is also the slope of the Linear regression line.

In Linear regression Model, the Model achieves a Linear regression line which is also known as a best fit line.
In the above snippet of plotted X and Y points, the Actual points and Linear regression line is plotted. The snippet says if the points were lying on the line or near it to it the model is said to be best fit or has good performance.
If the points are further away from the point, we calculate the u , the residual or error which is the difference between the Actual Point and predicted point on the Line.
In a Multivariate Regression Model:
 We have one dependent variable (y) and we have 2 or More independent Variable (xn). In Multivariate Regression Model the equation obtained will be:

       y=0  + 1x1 +2x2 ++ nxn

Where ,
1.y is the Response/Target or Simply known as Dependent Variable.
2.xn is the feature/predictor variable or simply known as independent Variable and n determines the number of independent variables.
3.0 is the Intercept, the intercept defines the minimum value of Y when x=0. Meaning it is the constant value and its not dependable on x.
4.n is the co-efficient of the independent variable and n determines the number of Co-efficient.

Regression of Sum of Squares:

The regression sum of squares describes how well a regression model represents the modeled data.

Error of Sum of Squares:

SSE is the sum of the squared differences between each observation and its group's mean.

  • Smaller the value of SSR or SSE, the more accurate the prediction will be, which would make the model the best fit.

      Multivaraite Regression Model

  • We Know the the Equation : y=mx+c is the Eqaution needs to be generated for a Linear Regression Model for one independent and dependent Varaible
  • Where m is the coefficient,c is the intercept,y is the dependent Variable and X is the Independent Variable
  • For a MultiVariate Regression, we have multiple Independent variables and one Dependent Variable .
  • Therefore, the Number of coefficients will be more depending on the independent Variables

    • Therefore for the given Business Model.

    In [12]:
    Data.columns
    Out[12]:
    Index(['Cement', 'Blast', 'Fly Ash', 'Water', 'Superplasticizer', 'CA', 'FA',
       'Age', 'CMS'],
      dtype='object')
  • Data.columns() gives you all the Varaibles of the dataset
  • Variables- Cement, Blast, Fly Ash, Water, Superplasticizer, CA , FA and Age are the inddependent Variables or Features
  • Variable- CMS is the dependent Variable/Target

    • Therefore, the Multivariate Regression Model Equation will be :

    y = a(x1) + b(x2) + c(x3) + d(x4) + e(x5) + f(x6) + g(x7) + h(x8) + c

    Where,

  • y=CMS
  • x1=Cement
  • x2=Blast
  • x3=Fly Ash
  • x4=Water
  • x5=Superplasticizer
  • x6=CA
  • x7=FA
  • x8=Age
  • a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,i are the Coefficients
  • c is the intercept

    Step 3:Standardization of the Data.

    Standardization of the Data is one of the most important step.Standardization comes into picture when features of input data set have large differences between their ranges, or simply when they are measured in different measurement units (e.g., Pounds, Meters, Miles etc).It is one of the pre-processing step.

  • StandardScaler is the function used to Standardize the data.It is imported from sklearn.preprocessing package.
    • fit_transform is used on the training data. The fit method is calculating the mean and variance of each of the features present in our data. The transform method is transforming all the features using the respective mean and variance and transforms the data in one format.
  • transform is used on the testng data.Using the transform method we can use the same mean and variance as it is calculated from our training data to transform our test data.

    The Ways to Improve the Performace of the Model:

  • Outliers:

    • There were Quiet a few Outliers in the Dataset. The Outliers need to be removed for the better performance of the Model.
    1.Remove the Outliers.
    OR

    OR
    3.Replace the outliers by the mean value

  • Dimensionality Reduction:

    • Dimension reduction, is the transformation of data from a high-dimensional space into a low-dimensional space so that the low-dimensional representation retains some meaningful properties of the original data, ideally close to its intrinsic dimension. Two Methods to perfrom Dimension Reduction:

    1. Principal Component Analysis.
      OR
    2. Linear Discrimant Analysis.
  • Larger Dataset And Normal Distributed Data:

    • 1.Conisder a Larger Dataset, to have a better Variation and less chance of Error.
    2.Make Sure the Data is a Normally Distributed. That means mean , median and mode are same or nearly same and standarad distribution is 1.
